{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518026"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:59:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:59:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12861"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12861"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.25,0.56,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5304"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77275"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5304"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12861"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62782"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"602"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1499"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"6190"},{"type":"tags","id":"6210"},{"type":"tags","id":"9546"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44880"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77275"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man who works as furniture removalist presents to the emergency department with lower back pain. He tells you that the pain started yesterday after a particularly hard day at work, and it has been getting progressively worse. He rates the pain as 8/10 currently. On further questioning, he reports that his entire left leg feels weak and it is difficult to move. He also reports an intermittent shooting pain in the left leg. He denies saddle anaesthesia or disturbances to his bowel or bladder function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeurological examination of his lower limbs reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESymmetrical appearance with regards to muscle bulk; no fasciculations\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal tone without clonus bilaterally\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPower in the right leg is 5/5 throughout all myotomes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPower in the left leg is 4/5 throughout all myotomes, largely limited by pain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatellar reflexes are preserved bilaterally\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAchilles reflex is present on the right but unable to be elicited on the left despite reinforcement i.e., Jendrassik manoeuvre\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlantars are downgoing bilaterally\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERectal exam and saddle sensation not performed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGait was not evaluated as the patient could not walk due to pain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left L4 Radiculopathy","Left L5 Radiculopathy","Left S1 Radiculopathy","Left S2 Radiculopathy","Cauda Equina Syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a left S1 radiculopathy (sciatica)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe achilles reflex assesses the S1 nerve root\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ES1 radicular pain typically courses down the posterior leg, posterior calf, and into the sole of the foot\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s S1 radiculopathy is most likely secondary to prolapse of the L5/S1 intervertebral disc (herniated nucleus pulposus).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt each level of the lumbar spine, there is is an \u0022exiting\u0022 and \u0022traversing\u0022 nerve root. The \u0022exiting\u0022 nerve root leaves exits immediately inferior to the pedicle and is usually not affected by a disc prolapse at the same level i.e., the L5 nerve root exits below L5 at the L5/S1 disc space but courses superiorly to the disc itself. By contrast, the \u0022traversing\u0022 nerve root (which exits at the level below) is vulnerable to compression i.e., the traversing root at L5/S1 is the S1 root. S1 exits at the S1/S2 interspace.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncorrect answers\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL4 radiculopathy\u003C/strong\u003E - L4 radicular pain typically courses into the medial calf. L4 radiculopathy may cause decreased patellar reflex and weak ankle dorsiflexion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL5 radiculopathy\u003C/strong\u003E - L5 radicular pain typically courses down the anterior leg into the hallux and is associated with weakness of ankle dorsiflexion (foot drop), hallux extension, and foot eversion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ES2 radiculopathy\u003C/strong\u003E - S2 radicular pain typically courses down the posterior leg. The S2 dermatome also includes the genital region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECauda equina syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E - Cauda equina syndrome refers to compression of the lumbosacral nerves inferior to the end of the cord. Red flags for caudal equina syndrome include saddle anaesthesia and incontinence (not present here). It is important to exclude this diagnosis in any patient presenting with lower back pain and neurological findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An S1 radiculopathy typically causes a shooting pain down the back of the leg, calf and into the sole of the foot (sciatica) and an absent ankle reflex","Herniation of the intervertebral disc typically causes compression of the traversing nerve root as opposed to the exiting root"],"references":["Berry JA, Elia C, Saini HS, Miulli DE. A Review of Lumbar Radiculopathy, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Cureus. 2019 Oct 17;11(10):e5934. doi: 10.7759/cureus.5934. PMID: 31788391; PMCID: PMC6858271.","Caridi JM, Pumberger M, Hughes AP. Cervical radiculopathy: a review. HSS J. 2011 Oct;7(3):265-72. doi: 10.1007/s11420-011-9218-z. Epub 2011 Sep 9. PMID: 23024624; PMCID: PMC3192889.","Alexander CE, Weisbrod LJ, Varacallo M. Lumbosacral Radiculopathy. 2024 Feb 27. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613587."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62782"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12861"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62782"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:29:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:29:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5304"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77275"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null